'''Markham's storm petrel''' ('''''Hydrobates markhami''''') is a [[seabird]] native to the Pacific Ocean around Peru, Chile, and Ecuador. The species is named after British explorer [[Albert Hastings Markham]], who collected the [[type specimen|specimen]] on which the [[Species description|scientific description]] was based. It is a large and slender storm petrel, with a wingspan between {{convert|49|and|54|cm|in|abbr=on}}. Its plumage is black to sooty brown with a grayish bar that runs diagonally across the upper side of the wings. A member of the family [[Hydrobatidae]], the northern storm petrels, the species is similar to the [[black storm petrel]] (''Hydrobates melania''), from which it can be hard to distinguish.

A [[Bird colony|colonial breeder]], this storm petrel nests in natural cavities in salt crusts in northern Chile and Peru; ninety-five percent of the known colonies are found in the [[Atacama Desert]]. The first colony was only reported in 1993, and it is expected that more colonies are yet to be discovered. Pairs produce one egg per season, which is laid on bare ground without any nesting material. Parents will attend their brood only at night, returning to the sea before dawn. The timing of the breeding season significantly varies both within and in between colonies, for unknown reasons. The diet of Markham's storm petrel consists of fish, [[cephalopod]]s such as [[octopus]]es, and [[crustacean]]s; about ten percent of stomach contents is traceable to scavenging.

The species is listed as [[Near-threatened species|near threatened]] by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN). Despite their relatively large population, which was estimated at between 150,000 and 180,000 individuals in 2019, the species is in decline. Primary threats are [[habitat destruction]] due to mining of the salt crusts the birds rely on for breeding, and [[light pollution]] by mines and cities near the colonies. Light pollution can attract or disorient fledglings that make their first flight to the sea, and has been estimated to be responsible for the death of around 20,000 fledglings each year, which might amount to one third of all fledglings.

==Taxonomy==
The ornithologist [[Osbert Salvin]] first [[species description|described]] Markham's storm petrel as ''Cymochorea markhami'' in 1883.<ref name="Oceanic_Birds" /><ref>{{cite journal | last=Salvin | first=Osbert | author-link=Osbert Salvin | year=1883 | title=List of the birds collected by Captain A. H. Markham on the west coast of America | journal=Proceedings of the Zoological Society of London | volume=1883 | issue=Part 3 | pages=419–432 [430] | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/28680274 | access-date=2020-06-02 | archive-date=2023-03-28 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230328013537/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/28680274 | url-status=live }}</ref> The species is named after [[Albert Hastings Markham]], a British explorer and naval officer who collected the [[type specimen]] off the coast of Peru.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /> In 1931, the ornithologist [[James L. Peters]] thought the bird was the same species as [[Tristram's storm petrel]] (''Oceanodroma tristrami''), though the two were later distinguished by the size of their {{birdgloss|tarsus|tarsi}} (the "lower leg" of a bird).<ref name="Oceanic_Birds" /><ref>{{cite book | editor1-last=Peters | editor1-first=James L. | editor1-link=James L. Peters | year=1931 | title=Check-List of Birds of the World | volume=1 | edition=1st | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | location=Cambridge, Massachusetts | pages=73–74 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14478128 | access-date=2023-11-25 | archive-date=2023-11-25 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231125162248/https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14478128 | url-status=live }}</ref> Subsequently, Markham's storm petrel was for many years considered a member of the genus ''[[Oceanodroma]]''.<ref name="Cornell_2020"/> In 1972, the ornithologist [[Reginald Wagstaffe]] considered Tristram's storm petrel a [[subspecies]] of Markham's storm petrel, though later research recognized them as different species.<ref>{{cite book|title=Systematics and Taxonomy of Australian Birds|editor1-last=Christidis|editor1-first=Lee|editor2-last=Boles|editor2-first=Walter E.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=klm159tsD-oC|isbn=978-0-643-06511-6|publisher=CSIRO Publishing|year=2008|page=82}}</ref>

In 2004 and 2017, genetic analyses found that the genus ''Oceanodroma'' must be merged with the genus ''Hydrobates'', because the only species of ''Hydrobates'', the [[European storm petrel]] (''Hydrobates pelagicus''), was found to be nested within ''Oceanodroma'' (i.e., some species of ''Oceanodroma'' are more closely related to the European storm petrel than to some other species of ''Oceanodroma'').<ref name="Nomenclature2004">{{Cite journal | last1=Penhallurick | first1=John | last2=Wink | first2=Michael | date=2004 | title=Analysis of the taxonomy and nomenclature of the Procellariiformes based on complete nucleotide sequences of the mitochondrial cytochrome b gene | journal=Emu – Austral Ornithology | volume=104 | issue=2 | pages=125–147 | doi=10.1071/MU01060| bibcode=2004EmuAO.104..125P | s2cid=83202756 }}</ref><ref name="WallaceMorris-Pocock2017">{{cite journal | last1=Wallace | first1=S.J. | last2=Morris-Pocock | first2=J.A. | last3=González Solís | first3=J.|last4=Quillfeldt|first4=P.|last5=Friesen|first5=V.L. | year=2017 | title=A phylogenetic test of sympatric speciation in the Hydrobatinae (Aves: Procellariiformes) | journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution | volume=107 | pages=39–47 | doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2016.09.025 | pmid=27693526 | doi-access=free| bibcode=2017MolPE.107...39W }}</ref> The name ''[[Hydrobates]]'' was introduced by the ornithologist [[Friedrich Boie]] in 1822 and thus has priority over the name ''Oceanodroma'', which was introduced by the ornithologist [[Ludwig Reichenbach]] in 1853. Therefore, all the species in ''Oceanodroma'' were transferred to ''Hydrobates'', including Markham's storm petrel, which was accepted by the [[International Ornithologists' Union]].<ref name=ioc>{{cite web | editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | date=July 2023 | title=Petrels, albatrosses | work=IOC World Bird List Version 13.2 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/petrels/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=25 November 2023 | archive-date=17 February 2022 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220217000647/https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/petrels/ | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1=Chesser | first1=R.T.  | last2=Burns | first2=K.J. | last3=Cicero | first3=C. | last4=Dunn | first4=J.L. | last5=Kratter | first5=A.W | last6=Lovette | first6=I.J. | last7=Rasmussen | first7=P.C. | last8=Remsen | first8=J.V. Jr | last9=Stotz  | first9=D.F. | last10=Winker  | first10=K. | year=2019 | title=Sixtieth supplement to the American Ornithological Society's ''Check-list of North American Birds'' |journal=The Auk |volume=136 | issue=3  |pages=1–23 |doi=10.1093/auk/ukz042 | doi-access=free }}</ref> The authors of the 2004 genetic study instead suggested that the species formerly in ''Oceanodroma'' should be split into smaller genera, placing Markham's storm petrel and its closest relatives in ''Cymochorea'', but this has not been followed by subsequent studies.<ref name="Nomenclature2004"/><ref name="Cornell_2020"/>

A genetic analysis by Wallace and colleagues in 2017 found Markham's storm petrel to be the [[sister taxon|sister species]] of the black storm petrel.<ref name="WallaceMorris-Pocock2017"/> This was subsequently questioned by Alvaro Jaramillo, who argued that Wallace and colleagues mistook a specimen of the black storm petrel for Markham's storm petrel. Therefore, the relationships of Markham's storm petrel to other members of its genus remain unclear.<ref name="Cornell_2020"/> The following [[cladogram]] shows the results of the 2017 study.<ref name="WallaceMorris-Pocock2017"/>

