The northern storm petrel family, Hydrobatidae, is a group of [[seabird]]s that is highly adapted to marine environments. ''Hydrobates'' is currently recognized as the only genus; its eighteen species are predominantly found in the northern hemisphere. They differ from their southern counterparts, the [[Austral storm petrel]]s (Oceanitidae), in having proportionally longer wings and shorter heads and legs. Fossils of storm petrels are rare, but have been found in [[Late Miocene|Upper Miocene]] deposits in California;<ref name="Handbook">{{ cite book | last=Carboneras | first=C. | year=1992 | chapter=Family Hydrobatidae (Storm-petrels) | editor1-last=del Hoyo | editor1-first=J. | editor2-last=Elliott | editor2-first=A. | editor3-last=Sargatal | editor3-first=J. | title=Handbook of the Birds of the World | volume=1: Ostrich to Ducks | location=Barcelona, Spain | publisher=Lynx Edicions | isbn=84-87334-10-5 | pages=258–271 [258–259] | chapter-url=https://archive.org/details/handbookofbirdso0001unse/page/258/mode/1up | chapter-url-access=registration }}</ref> by this time, the Hydrobatidae had probably extensively [[Evolutionary radiation|radiated]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Behaviour, Population Biology and Physiology of the Petrels|chapter=Evolution and Radiation|page=499|chapter-url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780127354156500119|publisher=Elsevier Ltd.|last=Warham|first=John|year=1996|isbn=978-0-12-735415-6|access-date=2023-02-14|archive-date=2023-02-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230214030425/https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/B9780127354156500119|url-status=live}}</ref> Both storm petrel families are in danger globally, the IUCN classifying 48% of the species as "near threatened" or higher.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hydrobatidae: Northern Storm-Petrels|url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/hydrob1/cur/introduction|last1=Winkler|first1=David W.|last2=Billerman|first2=Shawn M.|last3=Lovette|first3=Irby J.|journal=Birds of the World|year=2020|publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology|doi=10.2173/bow.hydrob1.01|s2cid=216364538|url-access=subscription|access-date=2023-02-28|archive-date=2023-02-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230228055642/https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/hydrob1/cur/introduction|url-status=live}}</ref> Markham's storm petrel breeds in extreme habitats in the Atacama desert; this breeding ecology is shared with [[Elliot's storm petrel]] and the [[ringed storm petrel]].<ref name="Norambuena2021"/>

Separate subspecies have not been identified, but a 2019 study suggested that the difference in breeding time between populations could lead to [[allochronic speciation]] ([[speciation]] occurring due to different breeding times between populations of a species) in the future.<ref name="Barros_2019"/><ref name="Cornell_2020">{{cite journal |last1=Drucker |first1=J. |last2=Jaramillo |first2=A. |year=2020 |editor1-last=Schulenberg |editor1-first=Thomas S |title=Markham's Storm-Petrel ''Hydrobates markhami'' |url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/maspet/cur/introduction |url-status=live |journal=Birds of the World |publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology |doi=10.2173/bow.maspet.01 |s2cid=216420851 |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201126020523/https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/maspet/cur/introduction |archive-date=2020-11-26 |access-date=2020-05-31}}</ref> A 2023 study found that there were three well-supported genetic clades of Markham's storm petrel, reflecting the {{lang|es|Paracas|italics=no}}, Arica, and Salar Grande colonies.<ref name="edge">{{cite journal |last1=Norambuena |first1=Heraldo V. |last2=Rivera |first2=Reinaldo |last3=Barros |first3=Rodrigo |last4=Silva |first4=Rodrigo |last5=Peredo |first5=Ronny |last6=Hernández |first6=Cristián E. |title=Living on the edge: genetic structure and geographic distribution in the threatened Markham's Storm-Petrel (''Hydrobates markhami'') |journal=PeerJ |date=2021 |volume=9 |article-number=e12669 |doi=10.7717/peerj.12669 |pmid=35036151 |pmc=8711276 |doi-access=free }}</ref> The researcher Rodrigo Barros and colleagues described the bird as "one of the least known seabirds in the world" in 2019.<ref name="Barros_2019" />

==Description==
[[File:Oceanodroma markhami by Roar Johansen.jpg|thumb|upright|alt=Flying dark bird with raised wings|right|Bird showing underside of wing west of [[Callao]], Peru]] 
Markham's storm petrel is a large and slender storm petrel. As in other species of its genus, the wings are slender with tapering tips and a distinct wing bend at the [[carpus]] (wrist). The tail is deeply forked. The fresh plumage is black to sooty brown with a dull lead-gray gloss on its head, neck, and {{birdgloss|mantle}}. With wear, the plumage becomes browner overall. A distinct crescent-shaped, grayish bar runs diagonally over the upper side of the inner wing. The [[covert feather]]s above this bar are often brownish, while the [[flight feather|primaries]] below it are often blackish, resulting in a characteristic three-colored wing pattern. The iris is brown and the bill, legs, and feet are black. The bill is shorter than in most related species, whereas the nasal tube on top of the bill is long, reaching to the mid-length of the beak.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /><ref name="Onley2007"/><ref name="Howell2012">{{cite book |last1=Howell |first1=Steve N. G. |title=Petrels, albatrosses, and storm-petrels of North America: a photographic guide |date=2012 |publisher=Princeton University Press |location=Princeton (N.J.) |isbn=978-0-691-14211-1 |pages=427–430}}</ref> Adults have a wingspan between {{convert|49|and|54|cm|in|abbr=on}} and measure between {{convert|21|and|23|cm|in|abbr=on}} from the tip of the bill to the tip of the tail.<ref name="Onley2007"/> Body weight is {{convert|53|g|oz|abbr=on}} on average.<ref name="Onley2007"/><ref name="Cornell_2020" /> Sexes are alike without [[Morphology (biology)|morphological]] differences.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /><ref name="Oceanic_Birds"/>

Similar birds within its range include the [[black storm petrel]] (''Hydrobates melania'') and the dark variety of [[Leach's storm petrel]] (''Hydrobates leucorhous''). It is especially difficult to distinguish from the similar-sized black storm petrel, from which it differs in having a tarsus that is much shorter than the foot, and in that the gray bar on the upper side of the wing is more distinct and reaches closer to the leading edge of the wing. Markham's storm petrel also differs in its shorter neck and more angular head, and in the more pronounced forking of the tail. From Leach's storm petrel, it differs in its more pronounced tail forking, its longer wings, and larger size. Differences in flight patterns also aid in separating these species. Markham's storm petrel typically flies leisurely and often glides with intermittent shallow wingbeats, whereas the black storm petrel glides less often and tends to use deep wingbeats. Markham's storm petrel also typically flies greater than {{convert|1|m|ft|abbr=on}} over the ocean surface, in contrast to the black storm-petrel, which usually flies at less than one meter. Leach's storm petrel generally uses deeper wingbeats and its flight is more bouncing.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /><ref name="Spear_2007">{{cite journal|title=Storm-Petrels of the Eastern Pacific Ocean: Species Assembly and Diversity along Marine Habitat Gradients|last1=Spear|first1=Larry B.|last2=Ainley|first2=David G.|publisher=American Ornithological Society|number=62|journal=Ornithological Monographs|year=2007|doi=10.2307/40166847|pages=8, 13, 27, 37–40|jstor=40166847}}</ref><ref name="Onley2007"/><ref name="Cornell_black-storm-petrel">{{cite journal|url=https://birdsoftheworld.org/bow/species/bkspet/cur/identification|last1=Everett|first1=W.T.|last2=Bedolla-Guzmán|first2=Y.R.|last3=Ainley |first3=D.G.|editor1-first=P.G.|editor1-last=Rodewald|title=Black Storm-Petrel – Identification|journal=Birds of the World|year=2021|publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology|doi=10.2173/bow.bkspet.01.1 |s2cid=243154613 |url-access=subscription}}</ref>

The [[Bird vocalization|calls]] of Markham's storm petrel have been described as series of "purrs", "wheezes", and "chatters".<ref name="Cornell_2020" /> Adults in nests were found to vocalize when a recording of Markham's storm petrel vocalizations was played at the entrance of the nest cavity.<ref name="Barros_2019" />

==Distribution and habitat==

[[File:Map of the phylogeographic structure of Hydrobates markhami.png|thumb|left|alt=Map showing coast of Peru and Chile with color-coding indicating populations of this bird|upright=1.7|Map showing the distribution of the main genetic [[clades]] of Markham's storm petrel, based on a 2021 study]] 
Markham's storm petrel inhabits waters of the [[Humboldt Current]] in the [[Pacific Ocean]] off Ecuador, Peru, and northern Chile.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /><ref name="Torres_2013">{{cite journal|last1=Torres-Mura|first1=Juan C.|last2=Lemus|first2=Marina L.|url=https://rchn.biologiachile.cl/pdfs/2013/4/13_Torres-Mura_and_Lemus.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181221111140/https://rchn.biologiachile.cl/pdfs/2013/4/13_Torres-Mura_and_Lemus.pdf|archive-date=December 21, 2018|title=Breeding of Markham's Storm-Petrel (''Oceanodroma markhami'', Aves: Hydrobatidae) in the Desert of Northern Chile|journal=Revista Chilena de Historia Natural|volume=86|year=2013|issue=4|publisher=Sociedad de Biología de Chile|pages=497–499|doi=10.4067/S0716-078X2013000400013|doi-access=free|bibcode=2013RvCHN..86..497T |url-status=live}}</ref> As these birds spend most of their lives at sea, they are considered to be [[endemic]] to the Humboldt Current.<ref name="Spear_2007" /><ref name="Gilman_2013"/> The birds may venture as far north as southern Mexico (18°N); as far south as central Chile (30°S); and as far west as 118°W. Sightings have been reported from even farther north, off [[Baja California]], but these might mistake Markham's storm petrel for the black storm petrel.<ref name="Crossin_1974">{{cite journal|title=Pelagic Studies of Seabirds in the Central and Eastern Pacific Ocean|editor-last=King|editor-first=Warren B.|last=Crossin|first=Richard S.|journal=Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology |year=1974|publisher=Smithsonian Institution Press|issue=158|page=187|doi=10.5479/si.00810282.158|hdl=10088/5305}}</ref><ref name="Spear_2007" /> A survey published in 2007 found that during austral autumn, the non-breeding season, the largest concentration of birds is just off the cost of Peru between [[Guayaquil]] and [[Lima]]. During spring, this concentration splits into two, with one concentration just off southern Peru and northern Chile, and a second concentration ca. {{cvt|1700|km}} to the west. Adults were more common within {{convert|200|km|abbr=on}} of the coast; subadults were more common at distances greater than {{convert|500|km|abbr=on}} from the coast. The birds were more common in the relatively shallow waters above the continental crust (the [[continental shelf]]) and less common in the deeper waters above the [[oceanic crust]], and more common in areas where the surface water is cooler and saltier.<ref name="Spear_2007" /> As a highly [[pelagic]] species, the birds are only rarely seen from shore.<ref name="Howell2012"/><ref name="Onley2007"/>

Despite its range, Markham's storm petrel only nests in Peru and Chile in the Atacama desert, in natural cavities in saltpeter (salt crusts rich in [[nitrate]]s).<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> The known colonies range in area from {{convert|33|to|6100|ha|abbr=on}}, with a density between 0.5 and 248 nests per hectare. They are typically located within {{convert|25|km|abbr=on}} of the sea, at an elevation of up to {{convert|1080|m|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /> The nesting habitats are typically flat areas devoid of vegetation, but in 2021, a colony ({{lang|es|Punta Patache|italics=no}}) was discovered close to a [[lomas]] (fog oasis), being the first known colony associated with abundant vegetation. The location of a colony likely depends on favorable wind corridors where the birds can take advantage of sea-land winds when returning to the nest after nightfall and land-sea winds when returning to the sea before dawn.<ref name="carevic_2023">{{cite journal |last1=Carevic |first1=Felipe S. |last2=Sielfeld |first2=Walter |last3=Alarcón |first3=Elena |last4=del Campo |first4=Alejandro |title=Discovery of a new colony and nest attendance patterns of two Hydrobates storm-petrels in the Atacama Desert of northern Chile |journal=The Wilson Journal of Ornithology |date=2023 |volume=135 |issue=3 |doi=10.1676/22-00109 |url=https://meridian.allenpress.com/wjo/article-abstract/doi/10.1676/22-00109/496677/Discovery-of-a-new-colony-and-nest-attendance |access-date=2023-12-06 |archive-date=2023-12-10 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231210012630/https://meridian.allenpress.com/wjo/article-abstract/doi/10.1676/22-00109/496677/Discovery-of-a-new-colony-and-nest-attendance |url-status=live |url-access=subscription }}</ref>

[[File:Chick H. markhami.webm|thumb|alt=Video of a bird sitting on the ground under a spotlight|right|Video of a Markham's storm petrel chick at a nest site in Chile]]
Because the birds only return to their nests after nightfall and fly off again to sea before dawn, the detection of the breeding colonies is difficult, and their location had long been unknown.<ref name="carevic_2023"/><ref name="Cornell_2020" /> The first colony, on the [[Paracas Peninsula]] of Peru, was only reported in 1993 and is estimated at 2,300 pairs.<ref name="carevic_2023"/><ref name="Jahncke_1993">{{cite book|last=Jahncke |first=Jamie |year=1993 |chapter=Primer informe del área de anidación de la golondrina de tempestad negra ''Oceanodroma markhami'' (Salvin, 1883)|trans-title=First report of the nesting area of Markham's storm petrel ''Oceanodroma markhami'' (Salvin, 1883)| editor=Castillo de Maruenda, E.|title=Memorias X Congreso Nacional de Biología|language=es| pages=339–343}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Jahncke|first=Jamie|title=Biología y conservación de la golondrina de tempestad negra ''Oceanodroma markhami'' (Salvin 1883) en la península de Paracas, Perú|trans-title=Biology and Conservation of Markham's storm petrel ''Oceanodroma markhami'' (Salvin 1883) in the Paracas Peninsula, Peru|year=1994|language=es|journal=Informe Técnico|publisher=APECO}}</ref> Five more colonies, all in northern Chile, were discovered between 2013 and 2021.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /><ref name="carevic_2023"/> Two separate discoveries occurred in Chile in 2013: one of nesting sites south of the [[Acha (Chile)|Acha valley]] in [[Arica Province]] and one of a recording of a bird singing. After further exploration in November 2013 based on the recording,<ref name="Torres_2013" /><ref name="Schmitt">{{cite journal | last1=Schmitt | first1=F. | last2=Rodrigo | first2=B. | last3=Norambuena | first3=H. | date=2015 | title=Markham's storm petrel breeding colonies discovered in Chile | journal=Neotropical Birding | volume=17 | pages=5–10 | url=http://www.neotropicalbirdclub.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/NB17-F1-Schmitt.pdf | access-date=2023-11-25 | archive-date=2023-11-18 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231118183454/http://www.neotropicalbirdclub.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/NB17-F1-Schmitt.pdf | url-status=live }}</ref> populations of 34,684 nests in [[Arica]], 20,000 nests in [[Salar Grande (caldera)|Salar Grande]], and 624 nests in {{lang|es|Pampa de la Perdiz|italics=no}} were found in the [[Atacama Desert]] of northern Chile, as reported in a 2019 study. This translated to about ninety-five percent of the known breeding population at the time. The authors of the study noted that there are two other areas in Chile that could hold colonies based on sightings of grounded fledglings; these would then be the southernmost colonies.<ref name="Barros_2019">{{cite journal|last1=Barros|first1=Rodrigo|last2=Medrano|first2=Fernando|last3=Norambuena|first3=Heraldo V.|last4=Peredo|first4=Ronny|last5=Silva|first5=Rodrigo|last6=de Groote|first6=Felipe|last7=Fabrice|first7=Schmitt|title=Breeding phenology, distribution and conservation status of Markham's Storm-Petrel ''Oceanodroma markhami'' in the Atacama Desert|journal=Ardea|volume=107|number=1|pages=75, 77–79, 81|year=2019|doi=10.5253/arde.v107i1.a1|s2cid=164959486}}</ref> The first breeding site of this species in south Peru was reported from [[Pampa Pie de Candela]] in 2023.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gallardo |first1=Benjamín |last2=Vizcarra |first2=Jhonson K. |last3=Peredo |first3=Ronny |last4=Gutiérrez |first4=Pablo |last5=Contardo |first5=Nelson |last6=Arcco |first6=Andy |last7=Medrano |first7=Fernando |title=Descubrimiento del primer sitio de reproducción de Golondrina de Mar Negra (''Hydrobates markhami'') en el extremo sur del Perú |journal=El Hornero |date=2024 |volume=38 |issue=2 |pages=63–69 |doi=10.56178/eh.v38i2.1438 |language=es | trans-title = Discovery of the first breeding site of Markham's storm petrel (''Hydrobates markhami'') in the south of Peru|doi-access=free }}</ref>

==Behavior and ecology==
[[File:Markham's Storm-Petrel nest.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Sand with a nest-hole in it seen from above|Nest hole in Chile]]
Like other storm petrels, Markham's storm petrel is probably [[monogamy in animals|monogamous]]. The reproductive cycle, from arrival at colonies to departure of fledglings, lasts about five months. Some pairs will begin breeding much earlier than others – for example, in three colonies (the Paracas, Arica, and {{lang|es|Salar de Quiña|italics=no}} colonies), some females lay their eggs in April, and others lay their eggs as late as August. This could lead to a 10-month reproductive season of the overall [[bird colony|colony]], contrasting with most other colony-forming birds in which breeding is much more synchronized. There are also large discrepancies between colonies: In three other colonies (the Caleta Buena, {{lang|es|Salar Grande|italics=no}}, and {{lang|es|Salar de Navidad|italics=no}} colonies), egg laying occurs much later, between November and probably February. The causes of these discrepancies are unknown.<ref name="Barros_2019" /><ref name="Cornell_2020" />

The entries to the nest cavities measure {{convert|9.33|cm|in|abbr=on}} in diameter on average, but range between {{convert|5.5|and|18|cm|abbr=on}}. The depth of the nest cavities was typically greater than {{convert|40|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name="Torres_2013"/> Storm petrel nests produce a characteristic strong smell that helps researchers confirm that nest cavities are in use.<ref name="Gilman_2013"/><ref name="carevic_2023"/> Pairs produce one egg per season, which is laid on bare ground inside the cavity without any lining.<ref name="Jahncke_1993" /><ref name="Cornell_2020" /> The eggs are pure white without gloss,<ref name="Oceanic_Birds" /> and measure {{convert|32.2|by|24.2|mm|abbr=on}} on average.<ref name="Jahncke_1993" /> The egg is incubated by both parents in shifts of up to three days, during which the other partner is feeding at sea. The average incubation period was 47 days in Paracas.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /> After the chick hatches, parents return to it with food every two to three days. At the {{lang|es|Punta Patache|italics=no}} colony, Markham's storm petrel tends to return to their nests after nightfall between 23:00 and 01:00 and leave between 04:00 and 06:00.<ref name="carevic_2023"/> Pairs of a colony do not [[Cooperative breeding|cooperate in breeding]].<ref name="Cornell_2020" />

