After hatching, in Chile, the fledglings move towards the sea after a chick phase.<ref name="SAG_2019">{{cite news|title=La triste historia de la golondrina de mar que se está perdiendo en la ciudad|trans-title=The Sad History of the Golondrina de Mar that is Getting Lost in the City|url=https://www.latercera.com/que-pasa/noticia/la-triste-historia-de-la-golondrina-de-mar-que-se-esta-perdiendo-en-la-ciudad/623058/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302071435/https://www.latercera.com/que-pasa/noticia/la-triste-historia-de-la-golondrina-de-mar-que-se-esta-perdiendo-en-la-ciudad/623058/|archive-date=March 2, 2020|language=es|last=Yáñez|first=Cecilia|date=April 21, 2019|newspaper=La Tercera|url-status=live}}</ref> Fledglings are either attracted to or disoriented by artificial lights, an occurrence common to burrow-nesting petrels.<ref name="Torres_2013"/><ref>{{cite journal|title=Seabird Mortality Induced by Land-based Artificial Lights|last1=Rodríguez|first1=Airam|last2=Holmes|first2=Nick D.|last3=Ryan|first3=Peter G.|last4=Wilson|first4=Kerry-Jayne |last5=Faulquier|first5=Lucie|last6=Murillo|first6=Yovana|last7=Raine|first7=André F.|last8=Penniman|first8=Jay F.|last9=Neves|first9=Verónica |last10=Rodríguez|first10=Beneharo|last11=Negro|first11=Juan J.|last12=Chiaradia|first12=André|last13=Dann|first13=Peter|last14=Anderson|first14=Tracy|last15=Metzger|first15=Benjamin|last16=Shirai|first16=Masaki|last17=Deppe|first17=Lorna|last18=Wheeler|first18=Jennifer |last19=Hodum|first19=Peter|last20=Gouveia|first20=Catia|last21=Carmo|first21=Vanda|last22=Carreira|first22=Gilberto P.|last23=Delgado-Alburqueque|first23=Luis|last24=Guerra-Correa|first24=Carlos|last25=Couzi|first25=François-Xavier|last26=Travers|first26=Marc|last27=Le Corre|first27=Matthieu|display-authors=5|journal=Conservation Biology|volume=31|number=5|publisher=Society for Conservation Biology|date=February 2017|page=989|doi=10.1111/cobi.12900|pmid=28151557|bibcode=2017ConBi..31..986R |hdl=10400.3/4515|hdl-access=free}}</ref> [[Molting]] in adults probably takes place between December and May, whereas juveniles probably molt several months earlier.<ref name="Howell2012"/><ref name="Onley2007">{{cite book|title=Albatrosses, Petrels and Shearwaters of the World|series=Helm Field Guides|year=2007|publisher=Christopher Helm|pages=232–233, 234|last1=Onley|first1=Derek J.|last2=Scofield|first2=Paul|isbn=978-0-7136-4332-9}}</ref> At sea, the birds are typically encountered alone or in small flocks, sometimes with other storm petrel species.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /> It usually does not accompany ships.<ref name="Onley2007"/>

A 2007 study found that a sample of fifteen Markham's storm petrels had consumed the fish ''[[Diogenichthys|Diogenichthys laternatus]]'' and ''[[Vinciguerria lucetia]]'', among other foods. Markham's storm petrel was found to have a lower dietary diversity than other small petrels, though dietary diversity was generally high among small petrels compared to other birds analyzed.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Foraging Dynamics of Seabirds in the Eastern Tropical Pacific Ocean|url=https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/sab/sab_035.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200608143046/https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/sab/sab_035.pdf|archive-date=June 8, 2020|last1=Spear|first1=Larry|last2=Ainley|first2=David|last3=Walker|first3=William|journal=Studies in Avian Biology|volume=35|publisher=Cooper Ornithological Society|year=2007|pages=1, 43, 73|url-status=live}}</ref> A 2002 study found its main diet by mass consisted of fish (namely the [[Peruvian anchoveta|Peruvian anchovy]], ''Engraulis ringens''), [[cephalopod]]s (namely the [[octopus]] ''[[Japetella|Japetella sp.]]''), and [[crustacean]]s (namely the [[Pleuroncodes monodon|pelagic squat lobster]], ''Pleuroncodes monodon''); about ten percent of analyzed stomach contents suggest scavenging. Based on large variations in the types of food it consumes, and its tendency to scavenge, Markham's storm petrel appears to opportunistically forage near the surface of the ocean.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=García-Godos|first1=Ignacio|last2=Goya|first2=Elisa|last3=Jahncke|first3=Jamie|title=The Diet of Markham's Storm Petrel ''Oceanodroma markhami'' on the Central Coast of Peru|url=http://www.marineornithology.org/PDF/30_2/4_garcia.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426195820/http://www.marineornithology.org/PDF/30_2/4_garcia.pdf|archive-date=April 26, 2018|journal=Marine Ornithology|year=2002|volume=30|number=2|pages=77, 79, 81–82}}</ref> The proportion of birds that feed or rest, compared to flying in transit, was significantly higher in austral autumn than spring according to the 2007 study.<ref name="Spear_2007" />

Predators of adults probably include larger birds such as [[skua]]s and large [[Larus|gulls]]. Two species of fox, the [[Sechura fox]] and the [[South American gray fox]], are important nest predators. Chicks are also known to be predated upon by [[birds of prey]], dogs, and the ant ''[[Pheidole chilensis]]''.<ref name="Cornell_2020" /> A 2018 study found the [[ectoparasitical]] stick-tight flea (''[[Hectopsylla|Hectopsylla psittaci]]'') on two birds out of ten captured in {{lang|es|Pampa de Chaca|italics=no}} within the [[Arica y Parinacota Region]]. Both specimens were found in the [[Lore (anatomy)|lorum]] (the region between the eyes and nostrils) on each bird. The [[turkey vulture]] (''Cathartes aura'') served as a possible source for the transition between hosts, as the two were observed nesting in the same colony.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cerpa|first1=Patrich|last2=Medrano|first2=Fernando|last3=Peredo|first3=Ronny|title=Saltos del desierto al mar: Presencia de la pulga ''Hectopsylla psittaci'' en la golondrina de mar negra (Oceanodroma markhami) en el norte de Chile| trans-title=Jumps from desert to the sea: presence of the stick–tight flea ''Hectopsylla psittaci'' in Markham's Storm–Petrel (''Oceanodroma markhami'') in the North of Chile|journal=Revista Chilena de Ornitología|publisher=Unión de Ornitólogos de Chile|volume=24|number=1|year=2018|language=es|pages=40–42|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/326093203}}</ref>

==Status and conservation==

The [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) estimated the population of Markham's storm petrel in 2019 as between 150,000 and 180,000 individuals, between 100,000 and 120,000 of them being mature.<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> The global breeding population has been estimated at 58,000 pairs.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Nuevos antecedentes sobre la historia natural y conservación de la golondrina de mar negra (ocenodroma markhami) y la golondrina de mar de collar (ocenodroma hornbyi) en Chile|trans-title=New Information on the Natural History and Conservation of Markham's Storm-petrel (''Oceanodroma markhami'') and Hornby's Storm-petrel (''Oceanodroma hornbyi'') in Chile|url=https://aveschile.cl/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Medrano-et-al-21-30.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200606041711/https://aveschile.cl/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Medrano-et-al-21-30.pdf|archive-date=June 6, 2020|last1=Medrano |first1=Fernando |last2=Silva |first2=Rodrigo |last3=Barros |first3=Rodrigo|last4=Terán|first4=Daniel|last5=Peredo|first5=Ronny|last6=Gallardo|first6=Benjamin|last7=Cerpa|first7=Patrich|last8=de Groote |first8=Felipe |last9=Gutiérrez |first9=Pablo |last10=Tejeda |first10=Ivo |display-authors=5 |journal=Revista Chilena de Ornitología |publisher=Unión de Ornitólogos de Chile|year=2019|volume=25|number=1|language=es|page=26|url-status=live}}</ref> A 2004 estimate placed the population at likely in excess of 30,000 individuals,<ref name="IUCN_2004">{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22698543/132652667|title=''Hydrobates markhami''|author=BirdLife International|year=2018|access-date=June 6, 2019}}</ref> a 2007 estimate placed it at between 806,500 in austral spring and 1,100,000 in austral autumn,<ref name="Spear_2007" /> and a 2012 estimate placed it at 50,000 overall individuals.<ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/22698543/37855907|title=''Hydrobates markhami''|author=BirdLife International|year=2012|access-date=June 6, 2019}}</ref> The IUCN estimates that the population of Markham's storm petrel is in decline, although the rate of decline is unknown as it is unclear how many juveniles die of natural causes.<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" />

Despite its large population, in 2019, the IUCN listed Markham's storm petrel as [[Near-threatened species|near threatened]].<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> Since at least 2012, the bird has been classified as endangered in Chile,<ref name="Torres_2013" /> and, in 2018, the Chilean [[Ministry of the Environment (Chile)|Ministry of the Environment]] (MMA) classified the bird as in danger of extinction.<ref name="MMA_2019">{{cite web|url=https://mma.gob.cl/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Resol_1113_sept_2019_incio_abreviado_RECOGE_golondrinas_de_mar.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200607005636/https://mma.gob.cl/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Resol_1113_sept_2019_incio_abreviado_RECOGE_golondrinas_de_mar.pdf|archive-date=June 7, 2020|title=Resolución exenta n° 1113: Da inicio al proceso de el aboración del plan de recuperación, conservación y gestión de las golondrinas del mar del norte de chile|trans-title=Exempt Resolution n° 1113: Initiates the Process of Drawing Up the Plan for the Recovery, Conservation and Management of the Golondrinas Del Mar of Northern Chile|language=es|date=September 11, 2019|publisher=Ministerio del Medio Ambiente}}</ref><ref name="Longino_2019">{{cite web|title=SAG inició campaña de difusión para rescate de golondrinas de mar negra|trans-title=SAG Started a Dissemination Campaign to Rescue Golondrinas de Mar Negra|url=https://www.diariolongino.cl/sag-inicio-campana-de-difusion-para-rescate-de-golondrinas-de-mar-negra/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200606185335/http://www.diariolongino.cl/sag-inicio-campana-de-difusion-para-rescate-de-golondrinas-de-mar-negra/|archive-date=June 6, 2020|date=March 19, 2019|language=es|work=El Longino}}</ref> In Ecuador, {{as of|2019|lc=y}}, the species is classified as Near Endangered by Ecuador's Ministry of Environment.<ref>{{cite web |title=Charles Darwin Foundation – Lista roja de aves del Ecuador |url=https://www.darwinfoundation.org/en/publications/identification-guides/lista-roja-de-aves-del-ecuador |website=www.darwinfoundation.org |access-date=3 February 2024}}</ref>

===Threats===

[[File:Rescue H. Markhami.jpg|thumb|alt=gloved human hands holding a dark bird|Rescued bird that had been attracted or disoriented by city lights near [[Iquique]], Chile]]
The main threats to this species are habitat destruction by saltpeter mining as well as [[light pollution]]. Saltpeter mining directly destroys nest holes and has been responsible for the loss of much breeding habitat.<ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> Light pollution by the mines, nearby cities, and roads causes significant mortalities as the fledglings are attracted or disoriented by artificial lights on their first flight to sea. The exhausted birds collide with buildings or land close to the lights, which has been termed "fallout".<ref name="Gilman_2013">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/07/storm-petrel-secret-desert-habitat-nests/563687/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200511094655/https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2018/07/storm-petrel-secret-desert-habitat-nests/563687/|archive-date=May 11, 2020|title=South America's Otherworldly Seabird|last=Gilman|first=Sarah|magazine=The Atlantic|date=July 20, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Norambuena2021">{{cite journal |last1=Norambuena |first1=H.V. |last2=Medrano |first2=F. |last3=Barros |first3=R. |last4=Silva |first4=R. |last5=Peredo |first5=R. |last6=Tejeda |first6=I. |title=More than just the driest desert in the world: a long and uncertain battle to conserve the storm petrels of the Atacama Desert |journal=Emu – Austral Ornithology |date=2021 |volume=121 |issue=3 |pages=267–269 |doi=10.1080/01584197.2021.1900742|bibcode=2021EmuAO.121..267N }}</ref> These fallen birds are often predated upon by turkey vultures after dawn.<ref name="Barros_2019" /> A 2019 study estimates that at least 20,000 fledglings die each year due to artificial lights, which might represent one third of the fledglings of the entire population.<ref name="Barros_2019" /> One mining company reported that 3,300 fledglings had been grounded due to their lights over a three-month span.<ref name="Gilman_2013"/>

Markham's storm petrel is also threatened by other impacts of human development in the Atacama desert.<ref name="Gilman_2013"/><ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> Reported threats include new construction and development especially of power lines, solar energy parks, wind farms, and roads, which may destroy breeding habitat; garbage from roads and landfills near the colonies, which can attract predators or be blown by wind to get stuck in and possibly block the entrances to nest holes; and military activities within the colonies.<ref name="Barros_2019" /><ref name="iucn status 12 November 2021" /> Bulldozer trails, dogs, and an encampment of road construction workers have been observed near nesting areas close to Arica.<ref name="Torres_2013" /> A 2023 study found that 16 of 25 fledglings and all adult Markham's storm petrels examined in Chile had human-made debris (such as plastic, rubber, and cotton) in their digestive tracts, which raised concern due to the known health impact of debris on other seabirds.<ref name="Debris">{{cite journal |last1=Medrano Martínez |first1=Fernando |last2=Vargas |first2=Macarena |last3=Terán |first3=Daniel |last4=Flores |first4=Marlene |last5=Álvarez |first5=Giannira |last6=Peredo |first6=Ronny |title=Ingestion of man-made debris by Markham's storm-petrel |journal=Marine Ornithology |date=2023 |volume=51 |pages=201–203 |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/374615401}}</ref>

Markham's storm petrel is particularly sensitive to the [[effects of climate change]] because it relies on saltpeter deposits as breeding habitat: Since saltpeter deposits are limited in distribution, there will be relatively few alternative breeding areas should the currently occupied ones become unsuitable. A 2021 simulation showed that by 2080, changes in temperature would lead to a moderate reduction in potential breeding habitat under benign climatic conditions, and to a large reduction under severe climatic conditions. The authors cautioned that their simulation does not take into account habitat loss due to human development, so that the actual habitat loss can be expected to be even more severe.<ref name="edge"/>

===Conservation efforts===

[[File:Markham's Storm-Petrel captured.jpeg|thumb|alt=Dark bird in a cardboard box|Captured bird in Chile]]
Conservation efforts have been described as challenging, and as of 2021, initiatives were mostly funded by the [[American Bird Conservancy]]. For Chile, a 2021 study criticized that the existing environmental legislation is "weak, favours industrial productivity and is insufficient to preserve the storm-petrels of the Atacama Desert".<ref name="Norambuena2021"/> Conservation efforts undertaken by the Chilean [[Ministry of Agriculture (Chile)|Ministry of Agriculture]] include the rescuing of fallen birds, including 2,000 individuals in 2018.<ref name="SAG_2019" />

The 2021 study suggested six management priorities to protect the storm petrels of the Atacama desert, including formal protection of colonies; regulation of infrastructure projects and other human activities to prevent impact on colonies; stricter environmental assessments for planned development projects that might affect breeding areas; the reduction of light pollution and the mitigation of its impacts; international cooperation; and further research.<ref name="Norambuena2021"/> Other authors likewise stressed the importance of more research for effective conservation efforts.<ref name="Gilman_2013"/><ref name="Cornell_2020" /> Suggested research priorities include the discovery of all breeding colonies, the mapping of the flight routes between colonies and the sea, the mapping of feeding areas at sea to possibly mitigate the impact of [[overfishing]], and the monitoring of population sizes.<ref name="Cornell_2020" />

